content.problemStatement:
In Java, the `super` keyword is used within a subclass to access **members (variables and methods)** from its **parent class**. This is helpful when both parent and child classes have members with the same name, or when the subclass needs to use functionality already defined in the parent.

The `super` keyword can also be used to **call the constructor** of the parent class to initialize inherited values.

---
 **Example Code:**

```java
// Parent class
class Animal {
    String name = "Animal"; // Variable in the parent class
}

// Child class that inherits from Animal
class Dog extends Animal {
    String name = "Dog"; // Variable in the child class with the same name

    // Method to display names from both child and parent classes
    void displayNames() {
        System.out.println("Child class name: " + name);        // Accesses child class variable
        System.out.println("Parent class name: " + super.name); // Uses 'super' to access parent class variable
    }
}

// Main class to run the program
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();         // Create an object of the Dog class
        d.displayNames();          // Call method to display both names
    }
}
```
**Expected Output:**

```default
Child class name: Dog
Parent class name: Animal
```

